{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17508043","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17508043"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:01:07+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:01:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2708"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2708","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2708"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.15,0.64,0.05,0.1,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2708"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80651"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2708","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2708"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2708"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65947"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"921"},{"type":"tags","id":"1184"},{"type":"tags","id":"4626"},{"type":"tags","id":"5937"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3394"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3395"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27027"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80651","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/80651"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 78-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with rapid onset of visual changes. He describes trouble visualising objects on the right side his vision and thinks that the centre of his vision is clearer. He is having difficulty describing objects as well as their use but can identify them when holding them and giving some direction. He is able to repeat statements and can give a meaningful history. He denies weakness or sensory changes. He has a medical history of hypercholesterolaemia, hypertension and obesity. He has a 40 pack-year smoking history but denies marijuanna use. He is right handed. On examination, his face appears symmetrical and there is no dysarthria. He has absent visual fields on the right side of both eyes with vision improving in the centre of both eyes. There is no nystagmus and extra-ocular movements are intact. He has 5/5 power and sensation is grossly intact.\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which of one the following cerebral blood vessels is most likely to be affected?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Right PCA","Left PCA","Right MCA","Left MCA","Basilar artery"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAll of the cerebral blood vessels have classical clinical syndromes based on the cortical lobes and subcortical areas they supply. Important to note is the handedness of the patient to help determine the dominant lobe, which in right handed people is usually the left and in left handed individuals it can be either way.\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe main cortical signs that occur in ACA, MCA, and PCA strokes include weakness, sensory disturbance, visual changes, aphasia (dominant lobe), and neglect (non-dominant).\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis patient describes right homonymous hemianopia with macular sparing. This is classical for a stroke affecting the left occipital lobe region which is supplied by the \u003Cstrong\u003Eleft PCA\u003C/strong\u003E. There is macular sparing in the majority of cases due to collateral supply by the distal MCA. There are many other symptoms/signs that can be present including \u003Cem\u003Evisual agnosia\u003C/em\u003E which is present in this patient. He has a nominal dysphasia secondary to a disconnect between the visual cortex and the language centres, which results in him struggling to attribute meaning to objects despite being able to see them. Using other brain centres such as tactile sensation allows him to identify the objects.\u00a0It is likely this patient would also have alexia - difficulty in reading as a result of damage to the visual cortex.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Homonymous hemianopia with macular sparing is indicative of a posterior cerebral artery (PCA) stroke.","Visual agnosia can occur in PCA strokes due to disconnection between the visual cortex and language centres."],"references":["Cereda C, Carrera E. Posterior cerebral artery territory infarctions. Front Neurol Neurosci. 2012;30:128-31. doi: 10.1159/000333610. Epub 2012 Feb 14. PMID: 22377879. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/22377879/","Kuybu O, Tadi P, Dossani RH. Posterior Cerebral Artery Stroke. StatPearls [Internet]. 2021. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK532296/.","Horton JC, Economides JR, Adams DL. The Mechanism of Macular Sparing. Annu Rev Vis Sci. 2021 Sep 15;7:155-179. doi: 10.1146/annurev-vision-100119-125406. Epub 2021 May 12. PMID: 33979527; PMCID: PMC8638601. Available from: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC8638601/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65947"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2708"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65947","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/65947"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-22T06:53:02+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-22T06:53:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2708"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80651"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-